comments.body:
> Do you also reorder items (ie member declarations) in a class?

Nope. Pure whitespace changes, AST must remain identical.

> align lines that are very similar

Could you be more specific here? For example, what if a def takes arguments or has explicit return type:

```scala
  def address = column[String]("address", O.PrimaryKey)
  def name(str: String) = column[String](str)
  def status = column[Int]("status")
  def statusWithReturnType: Column[Int]  = column[Int]("status")
```

> that's probably stuff for another issue.

I agree, but the implementation will rely on similar mechanics so I was curious to know your opinion :smile:

@paulp The last one is an actual bug, see #152.

The first three are fixable with configuration, although it is a bit awkward

```scala

 ollie  ~  dev  psp-std  scalafmt -f foo.scala  // no vertical alignment
object A {
  x match {
    case 1 => 2 -> 2 // this is a comment
    case 11 => 22 -> 22 // another one
    case 111 => 222 -> 222 // third!

    case 1111 => 1111 // Please ignore me, I'm a loner
  }
  trait B extends A
  trait BB extends A

  class B extends A
  class BB extends A

  type C = Int
  type CC = String

  trait Eq[-A] extends Any { def eqv(x: A, y: A): Boolean }
  trait Hash[-A] extends Any with Eq[A] { def hash(x: A): Int }
}

 ollie  ~  dev  psp-std  cat .scalafmt                                                                  master
--alignTokens =;Defn.(Va(l|r)|Def|Type),extends;Defn.*,{;Template,};Template,=>;Case,->;Term.ApplyInfix
 ollie  ~  dev  psp-std  scalafmt -c .scalafmt -f foo.scala // with vertical alignment
object A {
  x match {
    case 1   => 2   -> 2 // this is a comment
    case 11  => 22  -> 22 // another one
    case 111 => 222 -> 222 // third!

    case 1111 => 1111 // Please ignore me, I'm a loner
  }
  trait B  extends A
  trait BB extends A

  class B  extends A
  class BB extends A

  type C  = Int
  type CC = String

  trait Eq[-A]   extends Any            { def eqv(x: A, y: A): Boolean }
  trait Hash[-A] extends Any with Eq[A] { def hash(x: A): Int          }
}
```

There is a bug if you try to align by comments `//`, which I've described in #151

body:
Original:
```scala
    def address = column[String]("address", O.PrimaryKey)
    def name = column[String]("name")
    def status = column[Int]("status")
```

Scalafmt:
```scala
    def address = column[String]("address", O.PrimaryKey)
    def name = column[String]("name")
    def status = column[Int]("status")
```

I would like the input to look like this:
```scala
    def address = column[String]("address", O.PrimaryKey)
    def name    = column[String]("name")
    def status  = column[Int]("status")
```

Using 0.1.5
